//! **Phase 2** of the cubical build: the **face lattice** (cofibrations) and
//! **partial elements / systems** ÔÇö the judgmental apparatus that a later Kan phase
//! (`transp`/`hcomp`/`comp`/`Glue`) will consume. This phase is still **Kan-free**:
//! read `crate::cubical`'s module doc first (it covers the interval `I` and
//! `Path`/`PathP`, Phase 1), then this doc, before touching [`Cof`],
//! [`crate::term::Term::Sys`], or [`crate::term::Term::Partial`].
//!
//! # Cofibrations: the face lattice generated by `(i = 0)`/`(i = 1)`
//!
//! A **cofibration** (face formula) is built from atomic constraints `r = 0`/`r = 1`
//! (where `r` is any interval-classified term ÔÇö in a well-typed program, always
//! [`crate::term::Term::IZero`], [`crate::term::Term::IOne`], or a bound interval
//! variable, since nothing else can have inferred type `I`; see `crate::cubical`),
//! closed under **conjunction** (`Ôêº`), **disjunction** (`Ôê¿`), with **`Ôèñ`** (always)
//! and **`ÔèÑ`** (never ÔÇö this is what `(i = 0) Ôêº (i = 1)` decides to, since `I` has
//! exactly two distinct endpoints). This is the **face lattice** of standard cubical
//! type theory (CohenÔÇôCoquandÔÇôHuberÔÇôM├Ârtberg *Cubical Type Theory*, ┬º3; OrtonÔÇôPitts'
//! axiomatic account of cofibrations as a sub-object of the interval-indexed
//! presheaf topos): a finite Boolean-ish lattice with an explicit `ÔèÑ`/`Ôèñ` and
//! `Ôêº`/`Ôê¿`, decidable because every atom only ever pins a *finite* set of interval
//! variables to one of the two literal endpoints.
//!
//! ## Decision procedure
//!
//! [`Cof`] is normalized to **disjunctive normal form**: a union of *clauses*, each
//! clause a conjunction of atoms. A clause containing both `r = 0` and `r = 1` for
//! the *same* (structurally identical) `r` is dropped as unsatisfiable ÔÇö this is the
//! one nontrivial axiom of the lattice (`i0 Ôëá i1`) and is exactly where `(i = 0) Ôêº
//! (i = 1)` collapses to `ÔèÑ`. [`entails`] then decides `¤å Ôèó ¤ê` ÔÇö semantic entailment
//! over the free Boolean lattice on the atoms' subjects ÔÇö by recursively splitting
//! each clause of `¤å` on its unfixed variables (from `¤ê`'s support) until every
//! completion is decided; this always terminates (each split strictly shrinks the
//! set of unfixed variables) and never panics, satisfying "finite, decidable lattice
//! problem, kept total". [`is_false`] (`¤å Ôèó ÔèÑ`) and *validity* (`Ôèñ Ôèó ¤å`) are both
//! just calls to `entails`.
//!
//! **Cofibrations are not first-class terms.** Unlike `I` (a phantom classifier that
//! still appears as `Term::I`), a [`Cof`] never gets its own `Term` constructor and
//! is never a checkable value with a sort of its own ÔÇö it only ever occurs as
//! metadata attached to [`crate::term::Term::Sys`] (a system's list of guards) and
//! [`crate::term::Term::Partial`] (a partial type's single guard). This is a
//! deliberate simplification, mirroring why `I` itself is rejected as a `╬á`
//! domain/codomain (see `crate::cubical`): giving cofibrations their own sort would
//! require a whole new "face type" with its own formation/typing rules and its own
//! soundness argument for what can flow through it. Keeping `Cof` pure Rust data ÔÇö
//! carried alongside terms, substituted in lock-step with them, but never
//! *inferred* or *checked* as a value in its own right ÔÇö avoids that surface
//! entirely while still supporting everything Phase 2 asks for (systems,
//! compatibility, the `Partial` type former, boundary reduction).
//!
//! # Partial elements and systems
//!
//! [`crate::term::Term::Partial`]`(¤å, A)` is the type of elements of `A` available
//! only when `¤å` holds (`Checker::infer`'s `Term::Partial` arm: well-formed exactly
//! when `A` is a type and every atom subject in `¤å` has type `I`; it lives in the
//! same sort as `A`).
//!
//! [`crate::term::Term::Sys`]`[¤å_1 Ôåª t_1, ÔÇª, ¤å_n Ôåª t_n]` is a **system**: a partial
//! element defined on `¤å_1 Ôê¿ ÔÇª Ôê¿ ¤å_n`. It is *check-only* (see `Checker::infer`'s
//! `Term::Sys` arm, which rejects it) ÔÇö like an anonymous record literal, it needs
//! an expected `Partial ¤ê A` to know `A` and to check *coverage* (`¤ê Ôèó ¤å_1 Ôê¿ ÔÇª Ôê¿
//! ¤å_n`, i.e. wherever the expected guard holds, some branch is defined). Each
//! branch is then checked at `A`, and finally the **compatibility condition** is
//! enforced (`Checker::check`'s `check_sys`): for every pair of branches `i Ôëá j`
//! whose overlap `¤å_i Ôêº ¤å_j` is *not* `ÔèÑ` (i.e. could actually be inhabited), `t_i`
//! and `t_j` must be **definitionally equal** ÔÇö checked with the kernel's existing,
//! already-sound `is_def_eq`. This is exactly the compatibility rule of cubical type
//! theory's partial-element systems (Cohen et al., ┬º4): the pieces must literally
//! agree wherever they overlap, or the system doesn't denote a single partial
//! element at all.
//!
//! Reduction (`crate::reduce::Reducer::whnf`, and independently in
//! `crate::nbe::Nbe`): a system reduces to branch `t_i` as soon as `¤å_i` **is
//! currently `Ôèñ`** ÔÇö not just literally written as `Ôèñ`, but *decided* true by
//! [`is_true`] after whatever substitution got it there (e.g. `[(i=0)Ôåªt,(i=1)Ôåªu]`
//! reduces to `t` once `i` has been instantiated to `i0`, exactly like the task
//! asks). If no branch currently holds, the system is stuck (a valid normal form ÔÇö
//! nothing forces it further, same status as a neutral variable).
//!
//! # Soundness: still a conservative extension, still no `False`
//!
//! Phase 2 adds no way to manufacture a fibrant inhabitant out of nothing:
//!
//! 1. **`Cof` carries no data of its own.** It's inert bookkeeping (a decidable,
//!    total, boolean-valued classifier over a finite set of already-well-typed
//!    interval subjects) ÔÇö nothing infers or checks *against* a `Cof` as a value, so
//!    it cannot be "solved" the way a metavariable can, and it never appears as the
//!    domain or codomain of a `╬á` (only inside `Sys`/`Partial`, both of which are
//!    ordinary structural positions, subject to ordinary structural/definitional
//!    equality ÔÇö see the new `compare`/`is_def_eq`/`conv` cases, all purely
//!    structural plus the one new reduction rule below).
//! 2. **`check_sys`'s compatibility check can only ever *reject*.** It calls
//!    `is_def_eq`, an already-proven-sound relation, and only to *gate* acceptance
//!    of a term ÔÇö never to *produce* a new proof term or a new equation between
//!    unrelated closed values. An incompatible system is a type error, full stop
//!    (see the adversarial test `incompatible_system_is_rejected` below).
//! 3. **The one reduction rule is a case split on already-decided data, not a
//!    computation that invents anything.** `[¤å_1 Ôåª t_1, ÔÇª] Ôåª t_i` when `¤å_i` is
//!    (decidably, statically) `Ôèñ` simply *selects* one of the branches the user
//!    already supplied and already had type-checked at `A` ÔÇö it doesn't synthesize
//!    a value of `A` where none was given. Compare: this is exactly as safe as
//!    ╬╣-reduction picking a constructor's already-checked case, not a new source of
//!    axioms.
//! 4. **Still nothing that fills an open box.** No `transp`/`hcomp`/`comp`/`Glue` ÔÇö a
//!    `Partial ¤å A` with an *incompatible or non-covering* system is simply
//!    ill-typed, and even a *well-typed* `Sys`/`Partial` is still just data sitting
//!    at a type, exactly like `Path` in Phase 1: nothing here can transport a term
//!    from one type to another, or turn a `Partial` into a total element of `A`
//!    outside the boundary it was literally given on. That's precisely the Kan
//!    phase's job, and it's still not implemented.
//!
//! Net effect: cofibrations are a decidable classical logic bolted onto the term
//! language as inert metadata, and systems are compatibility-checked partial data ÔÇö
//! exactly what the task calls for, and still strictly short of anything that can
//! prove `False` or equate two genuinely distinct closed values.
//!
//! # What's deferred to Phase 3 (Kan)
//!
//! `transp`/`J`-for-`Path`, `hcomp`/`comp` (composition ÔÇö filling an open box using
//! exactly the `Sys`/`Partial` apparatus built here as the *shape* of the box), and
//! `Glue` types are still entirely out of scope. Phase 2 builds the vocabulary
//! (faces, partial elements, compatibility) that Phase 3's Kan operations will
//! consume as their open-box argument; it does not itself add any operation that
//! *fills* one.

use crate::level::Level;
use crate::term::Term;

/// An atomic face constraint: `r = 0` or `r = 1`, where `r` is an interval-classified
/// term (see the module doc ÔÇö in a well-typed program, `IZero`, `IOne`, or a bound
/// interval variable).
#[derive(Clone, PartialEq, Eq, Debug)]
pub enum Atom {
    Eq0(Term),
    Eq1(Term),
}

/// A cofibration (face formula): the face lattice generated by [`Atom`]s under `Ôêº`
/// (`And`), `Ôê¿` (`Or`), with explicit `Ôèñ` (`Top`) and `ÔèÑ` (`Bot`). See the module doc
/// for the decision procedure ([`entails`]/[`is_false`]/[`is_true`]).
#[derive(Clone, PartialEq, Eq, Debug)]
pub enum Cof {
    Bot,
    Top,
    Atom(Atom),
    And(std::rc::Rc<Cof>, std::rc::Rc<Cof>),
    Or(std::rc::Rc<Cof>, std::rc::Rc<Cof>),
}

impl Cof {
    pub fn bot() -> Cof {
        Cof::Bot
    }
    pub fn top() -> Cof {
        Cof::Top
    }
    pub fn eq0(t: Term) -> Cof {
        Cof::Atom(Atom::Eq0(t))
    }
    pub fn eq1(t: Term) -> Cof {
        Cof::Atom(Atom::Eq1(t))
    }
    pub fn and(a: Cof, b: Cof) -> Cof {
        Cof::And(std::rc::Rc::new(a), std::rc::Rc::new(b))
    }
    pub fn or(a: Cof, b: Cof) -> Cof {
        Cof::Or(std::rc::Rc::new(a), std::rc::Rc::new(b))
    }

    /// Re-index free variables in every atom's subject (mirrors [`Term::lift`] ÔÇö a
    /// `Cof` carries no binders of its own, so this is purely a pass-through onto
    /// the atom subjects, at whatever `cutoff` the surrounding `Term::lift` call is
    /// at when it reaches a `Sys`/`Partial` node).
    pub fn lift(&self, amount: isize, cutoff: usize) -> Cof {
        match self {
            Cof::Bot => Cof::Bot,
            Cof::Top => Cof::Top,
            Cof::Atom(Atom::Eq0(t)) => Cof::eq0(t.lift(amount, cutoff)),
            Cof::Atom(Atom::Eq1(t)) => Cof::eq1(t.lift(amount, cutoff)),
            Cof::And(a, b) => Cof::and(a.lift(amount, cutoff), b.lift(amount, cutoff)),
            Cof::Or(a, b) => Cof::or(a.lift(amount, cutoff), b.lift(amount, cutoff)),
        }
    }

    /// Substitute `replacement` for the variable at de Bruijn `depth` in every atom's
    /// subject (mirrors [`Term::subst_at`]).
    pub fn subst(&self, depth: usize, replacement: &Term) -> Cof {
        match self {
            Cof::Bot => Cof::Bot,
            Cof::Top => Cof::Top,
            Cof::Atom(Atom::Eq0(t)) => Cof::eq0(t.subst_at(depth, replacement)),
            Cof::Atom(Atom::Eq1(t)) => Cof::eq1(t.subst_at(depth, replacement)),
            Cof::And(a, b) => Cof::and(a.subst(depth, replacement), b.subst(depth, replacement)),
            Cof::Or(a, b) => Cof::or(a.subst(depth, replacement), b.subst(depth, replacement)),
        }
    }

    /// [`Term::instantiate`]'s analogue: substitute `Var(0)`.
    pub fn instantiate(&self, arg: &Term) -> Cof {
        self.subst(0, arg)
    }

    /// Mirrors [`Term::subst_ctx`]'s parallel-substitution-of-a-block, at a given
    /// depth (used when `Cof`-carrying nodes sit under the elaborator's telescope
    /// re-expression).
    pub fn subst_ctx_go(&self, images: &[Term], depth: usize) -> Cof {
        match self {
            Cof::Bot => Cof::Bot,
            Cof::Top => Cof::Top,
            Cof::Atom(Atom::Eq0(t)) => Cof::eq0(t.subst_ctx_go(images, depth)),
            Cof::Atom(Atom::Eq1(t)) => Cof::eq1(t.subst_ctx_go(images, depth)),
            Cof::And(a, b) => {
                Cof::and(a.subst_ctx_go(images, depth), b.subst_ctx_go(images, depth))
            }
            Cof::Or(a, b) => Cof::or(a.subst_ctx_go(images, depth), b.subst_ctx_go(images, depth)),
        }
    }

    /// Mirrors [`Term::instantiate_levels`].
    pub fn instantiate_levels(&self, args: &[Level]) -> Cof {
        match self {
            Cof::Bot => Cof::Bot,
            Cof::Top => Cof::Top,
            Cof::Atom(Atom::Eq0(t)) => Cof::eq0(t.instantiate_levels(args)),
            Cof::Atom(Atom::Eq1(t)) => Cof::eq1(t.instantiate_levels(args)),
            Cof::And(a, b) => {
                Cof::and(a.instantiate_levels(args), b.instantiate_levels(args))
            }
            Cof::Or(a, b) => Cof::or(a.instantiate_levels(args), b.instantiate_levels(args)),
        }
    }

    /// Mirrors [`Term::has_meta`].
    pub fn has_meta(&self) -> bool {
        match self {
            Cof::Bot | Cof::Top => false,
            Cof::Atom(Atom::Eq0(t)) | Cof::Atom(Atom::Eq1(t)) => t.has_meta(),
            Cof::And(a, b) | Cof::Or(a, b) => a.has_meta() || b.has_meta(),
        }
    }

    /// A readable rendering for diagnostics (mirrors [`Term::pretty`]'s per-node `pp`,
    /// sharing the same binder-name buffer so nested interval binders print
    /// consistently).
    pub fn pp(&self, names: &mut Vec<String>) -> String {
        match self {
            Cof::Bot => "ÔèÑ".to_string(),
            Cof::Top => "Ôèñ".to_string(),
            Cof::Atom(Atom::Eq0(t)) => format!("({} = i0)", t.pp(names, 3)),
            Cof::Atom(Atom::Eq1(t)) => format!("({} = i1)", t.pp(names, 3)),
            Cof::And(a, b) => format!("({} Ôêº {})", a.pp(names), b.pp(names)),
            Cof::Or(a, b) => format!("({} Ôê¿ {})", a.pp(names), b.pp(names)),
        }
    }
}

/// Does `t` mention the bound variable at de Bruijn index `k` in any atom's subject
/// (mirrors `term::mentions_var`, used by [`Term::pretty`] to decide dependent-`╬á`
/// printing ÔÇö exposed here so `term.rs` can delegate for `Sys`/`Partial` nodes)?
pub(crate) fn mentions_var(phi: &Cof, k: usize) -> bool {
    match phi {
        Cof::Bot | Cof::Top => false,
        Cof::Atom(Atom::Eq0(t)) | Cof::Atom(Atom::Eq1(t)) => crate::term::mentions_var(t, k),
        Cof::And(a, b) | Cof::Or(a, b) => mentions_var(a, k) || mentions_var(b, k),
    }
}

/// A conjunctive clause: a finite set of atoms, all required to hold simultaneously.
/// `Vec::new()` is the empty conjunction, `Ôèñ`.
type Clause = Vec<Atom>;

/// Does an atom's subject reduce to a *literal* endpoint (so the atom itself is
/// statically `Ôèñ`/`ÔèÑ` regardless of any other variable)? `None` means the subject is
/// still a genuine (unresolved) interval variable.
fn literal_atom(a: &Atom) -> Option<bool> {
    match a {
        Atom::Eq0(Term::IZero) => Some(true),
        Atom::Eq0(Term::IOne) => Some(false),
        Atom::Eq1(Term::IZero) => Some(false),
        Atom::Eq1(Term::IOne) => Some(true),
        _ => None,
    }
}

/// Does `clause` contain both `r = 0` and `r = 1` for the same (structurally
/// identical) subject `r`? This is the one nontrivial axiom of the face lattice
/// (`i0 Ôëá i1`).
fn self_contradictory(clause: &Clause) -> bool {
    clause.iter().any(|a| match a {
        Atom::Eq0(t) => clause.iter().any(|b| matches!(b, Atom::Eq1(u) if u == t)),
        Atom::Eq1(t) => clause.iter().any(|b| matches!(b, Atom::Eq0(u) if u == t)),
    })
}

/// Disjunctive normal form: a set of satisfiable clauses (contradictory clauses, and
/// atoms that are literally `Ôèñ`/`ÔèÑ`, are simplified away as they're built). `ÔèÑ` is
/// the empty `Vec` (no satisfiable disjunct); `Ôèñ` is `vec![vec![]]` (one disjunct,
/// the empty/vacuous conjunction).
fn to_dnf(phi: &Cof) -> Vec<Clause> {
    match phi {
        Cof::Bot => Vec::new(),
        Cof::Top => vec![Vec::new()],
        Cof::Atom(a) => match literal_atom(a) {
            Some(true) => vec![Vec::new()],
            Some(false) => Vec::new(),
            None => vec![vec![a.clone()]],
        },
        Cof::And(a, b) => {
            let da = to_dnf(a);
            let db = to_dnf(b);
            let mut out = Vec::new();
            for ca in &da {
                for cb in &db {
                    let mut merged = ca.clone();
                    for atom in cb {
                        if !merged.contains(atom) {
                            merged.push(atom.clone());
                        }
                    }
                    if !self_contradictory(&merged) {
                        out.push(merged);
                    }
                }
            }
            out
        }
        Cof::Or(a, b) => {
            let mut out = to_dnf(a);
            out.extend(to_dnf(b));
            out
        }
    }
}

/// The distinct atom subjects mentioned across a set of clauses (deduped by
/// structural `Term` equality ÔÇö sufficient, since after `to_dnf` every subject is
/// either a literal endpoint (already eliminated by [`literal_atom`]) or a genuine
/// bound-variable-shaped interval term compared exactly as `Term`'s derived `Eq`
/// would).
fn subjects(clauses: &[Clause]) -> Vec<Term> {
    let mut out: Vec<Term> = Vec::new();
    for clause in clauses {
        for atom in clause {
            let t = match atom {
                Atom::Eq0(t) | Atom::Eq1(t) => t,
            };
            if !out.contains(t) {
                out.push(t.clone());
            }
        }
    }
    out
}

/// Does `clause` (a satisfiable partial assignment) already fix everything `target`
/// (another clause) needs ÔÇö i.e. does `clause`'s sub-cube sit inside `target`'s?
fn clause_covers(clause: &Clause, target: &Clause) -> bool {
    target.iter().all(|a| clause.contains(a))
}

/// Does every completion of `clause` (over the variables `target` cares about, that
/// `clause` doesn't already fix) land in some clause of `target`? Terminates because
/// each recursive call fixes one more previously-free variable.
fn clause_entails_dnf(clause: &Clause, target: &[Clause]) -> bool {
    if target.iter().any(|d| clause_covers(clause, d)) {
        return true;
    }
    let free_var = subjects(target)
        .into_iter()
        .find(|v| !clause.iter().any(|a| matches!(a, Atom::Eq0(t) | Atom::Eq1(t) if t == v)));
    match free_var {
        None => false,
        Some(v) => {
            let mut c0 = clause.clone();
            c0.push(Atom::Eq0(v.clone()));
            let mut c1 = clause.clone();
            c1.push(Atom::Eq1(v));
            // `c0`/`c1` might themselves be self-contradictory if `clause` already
            // pins `v`'s "twin" some other way ÔÇö but `v` was chosen precisely because
            // `clause` doesn't mention it yet, so neither extension can contradict
            // `clause`'s own atoms; a fresh `v = 0`/`v = 1` pair is never mutually
            // contradictory with itself either. So both branches are well-formed
            // (possibly-unsatisfiable-elsewhere, but that's fine: an unsatisfiable
            // branch entails anything, and `clause_entails_dnf` is only ever asked
            // about branches built this way, so it never needs to special-case it).
            clause_entails_dnf(&c0, target) && clause_entails_dnf(&c1, target)
        }
    }
}

/// **Cofibration entailment**: `¤å Ôèó ¤ê`, i.e. every point of the interval-cube
/// satisfying `¤å` also satisfies `¤ê`. Decidable and total (see the module doc for
/// the algorithm and its termination argument).
pub fn entails(phi: &Cof, psi: &Cof) -> bool {
    let dphi = to_dnf(phi);
    let dpsi = to_dnf(psi);
    dphi.iter().all(|c| clause_entails_dnf(c, &dpsi))
}

/// Is `phi` unsatisfiable (`¤å Ôèó ÔèÑ`)? E.g. `(i = 0) Ôêº (i = 1)`.
pub fn is_false(phi: &Cof) -> bool {
    entails(phi, &Cof::Bot)
}

/// Is `phi` valid, i.e. does it hold unconditionally (`Ôèñ Ôèó ¤å`)? Used by the
/// reduction rule: a system's branch fires once its guard is *decided* true, not
/// merely satisfiable.
pub fn is_true(phi: &Cof) -> bool {
    entails(&Cof::Top, phi)
}

/// Semantic equivalence of two cofibrations (`¤å Ôèó ¤ê` and `¤ê Ôèó ¤å`) ÔÇö used as the
/// definitional-equality relation on `Partial`/`Sys` guards (see `crate::cubical`'s
/// treatment of `╬á`, where grades are erased from identity: here, two guards that
/// pick out the same sub-cube are the "same" restriction even if built with
/// syntactically different `Ôêº`/`Ôê¿` trees).
pub fn cof_equiv(phi: &Cof, psi: &Cof) -> bool {
    entails(phi, psi) && entails(psi, phi)
}

#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use super::*;
    use crate::term::Term;

    fn v(i: usize) -> Term {
        Term::Var(i)
    }

    // ---- literal endpoints ----

    #[test]
    fn i0_eq_0_is_true() {
        assert!(is_true(&Cof::eq0(Term::IZero)));
    }
    #[test]
    fn i1_eq_0_is_false() {
        assert!(is_false(&Cof::eq0(Term::IOne)));
    }
    #[test]
    fn i0_eq_1_is_false() {
        assert!(is_false(&Cof::eq1(Term::IZero)));
    }
    #[test]
    fn i1_eq_1_is_true() {
        assert!(is_true(&Cof::eq1(Term::IOne)));
    }

    // ---- the 0Ôëá1 clash ----

    #[test]
    fn i_eq_0_and_i_eq_1_is_false() {
        let phi = Cof::and(Cof::eq0(v(0)), Cof::eq1(v(0)));
        assert!(is_false(&phi));
    }

    #[test]
    fn distinct_variables_pinned_differently_is_not_false() {
        // (i = 0) Ôêº (j = 1) ÔÇö no clash, since i Ôëá j (different Var indices).
        let phi = Cof::and(Cof::eq0(v(0)), Cof::eq1(v(1)));
        assert!(!is_false(&phi));
    }

    // ---- Ôèñ/ÔèÑ ----

    #[test]
    fn top_is_true_bot_is_false() {
        assert!(is_true(&Cof::top()));
        assert!(is_false(&Cof::bot()));
        assert!(!is_true(&Cof::bot()));
        assert!(!is_false(&Cof::top()));
    }

    // ---- entailment battery ----

    #[test]
    fn entailment_is_reflexive() {
        let phi = Cof::or(Cof::eq0(v(0)), Cof::eq1(v(0)));
        assert!(entails(&phi, &phi));
    }

    #[test]
    fn bot_entails_everything() {
        assert!(entails(&Cof::bot(), &Cof::eq0(v(0))));
        assert!(entails(&Cof::bot(), &Cof::bot()));
    }

    #[test]
    fn everything_entails_top() {
        assert!(entails(&Cof::eq0(v(0)), &Cof::top()));
        assert!(entails(&Cof::bot(), &Cof::top()));
    }

    #[test]
    fn top_only_entails_top() {
        assert!(entails(&Cof::top(), &Cof::top()));
        assert!(!entails(&Cof::top(), &Cof::eq0(v(0))));
    }

    /// Absorption: `(i=0) Ôêº ((i=0) Ôê¿ (j=1)) Ôëí (i=0)`.
    #[test]
    fn absorption() {
        let i0 = Cof::eq0(v(0));
        let lhs = Cof::and(i0.clone(), Cof::or(i0.clone(), Cof::eq1(v(1))));
        assert!(cof_equiv(&lhs, &i0));
    }

    /// `(i=0) Ôê¿ (i=1)` is the whole interval "boundary" ÔÇö it does *not* entail
    /// either endpoint alone, and neither endpoint alone entails the disjunction's
    /// negation-shaped things (there's no negation, but reflexivity/asymmetry checks
    /// stand in).
    #[test]
    fn boundary_disjunction_is_not_equivalent_to_either_endpoint() {
        let i0 = Cof::eq0(v(0));
        let i1 = Cof::eq1(v(0));
        let boundary = Cof::or(i0.clone(), i1.clone());
        assert!(entails(&i0, &boundary));
        assert!(entails(&i1, &boundary));
        assert!(!entails(&boundary, &i0));
        assert!(!entails(&boundary, &i1));
    }

    #[test]
    fn conjunction_is_stronger_than_either_conjunct() {
        let i0 = Cof::eq0(v(0));
        let j1 = Cof::eq1(v(1));
        let conj = Cof::and(i0.clone(), j1.clone());
        assert!(entails(&conj, &i0));
        assert!(entails(&conj, &j1));
        assert!(!entails(&i0, &conj)); // i=0 alone doesn't pin j=1
    }

    #[test]
    fn or_is_commutative_and_and_is_commutative_semantically() {
        let a = Cof::eq0(v(0));
        let b = Cof::eq1(v(1));
        assert!(cof_equiv(&Cof::or(a.clone(), b.clone()), &Cof::or(b.clone(), a.clone())));
        assert!(cof_equiv(&Cof::and(a.clone(), b.clone()), &Cof::and(b, a)));
    }

    #[test]
    fn de_morgan_style_distribution_and_over_or() {
        // (i=0) Ôêº ((j=0) Ôê¿ (j=1)) Ôëí ((i=0)Ôêº(j=0)) Ôê¿ ((i=0)Ôêº(j=1))
        let i0 = Cof::eq0(v(0));
        let j0 = Cof::eq0(v(1));
        let j1 = Cof::eq1(v(1));
        let lhs = Cof::and(i0.clone(), Cof::or(j0.clone(), j1.clone()));
        let rhs = Cof::or(Cof::and(i0.clone(), j0), Cof::and(i0, j1));
        assert!(cof_equiv(&lhs, &rhs));
    }
}

/// Kernel-integration tests: `Partial`/`Sys` typing, the compatibility condition,
/// system reduction, and the required adversarial soundness checks (see this
/// module's doc comment and the task's "no `False`" requirement).
#[cfg(test)]
mod kernel_tests {
    use super::*;
    use crate::kernel::Kernel;
    use crate::term::name;

    fn cn(s: &str) -> Term {
        Term::cnst(name(s), vec![])
    }

    /// `A B : Type 0`, `a b c : A`.
    fn base_env() -> Kernel {
        let mut k = Kernel::new();
        k.add_axiom("A", 0, Term::typ(0)).unwrap();
        k.add_axiom("a", 0, cn("A")).unwrap();
        k.add_axiom("b", 0, cn("A")).unwrap();
        k.add_axiom("c", 0, cn("A")).unwrap();
        k
    }

    /// `Partial ¤å A` is well-formed and lives in `A`'s own sort, for a genuine
    /// interval-classified guard.
    #[test]
    fn partial_type_wellformed() {
        let k = base_env();
        // Ôƒ¿iÔƒ® Partial (i=0) A  ÔÇö an interval binder around a Partial type.
        let ty = Term::plam(Term::partial(Cof::eq0(Term::Var(0)), cn("A").lift(1, 0)));
        // `PLam`'s endpoints need `Partial (i=0) A` and `Partial (i=1) A` to be
        // well-formed types; infer succeeds iff they are.
        let inferred = k.infer(&ty).unwrap();
        // Its type is `PathP (╬╗i. Sort ...) ...` ÔÇö just confirm inference succeeded
        // and the result is a `PathP`.
        assert!(matches!(inferred, Term::PathP(..)));
    }

    /// A cofibration atom whose subject is *not* interval-classified is rejected ÔÇö
    /// cofibrations can't smuggle ordinary data through an atom's subject.
    #[test]
    fn partial_rejects_non_interval_atom_subject() {
        let k = base_env();
        let bad = Term::partial(Cof::eq0(cn("a")), cn("A")); // `a : A`, not `: I`
        assert!(k.infer(&bad).is_err());
    }

    /// A single-branch system covering its whole guard checks fine and reduces to
    /// that branch once the guard is decided true.
    #[test]
    fn single_branch_system_checks_and_reduces() {
        let k = base_env();
        let ty = Term::partial(Cof::eq0(Term::IZero), cn("A"));
        let sys = Term::sys(vec![(Cof::eq0(Term::IZero), cn("a"))]);
        k.check(&sys, &ty).unwrap();
        let reducer = crate::reduce::Reducer::new(k.env());
        assert!(reducer.is_def_eq(&sys, &cn("a")));
    }

    /// The two-branch boundary system `[(i=0)Ôåªa, (i=1)Ôåªb]` checks against
    /// `Partial ((i=0)Ôê¿(i=1)) A` (coverage holds, and the branches don't overlap so
    /// compatibility is vacuous), and reduces to the right endpoint once `i` is
    /// substituted.
    #[test]
    fn boundary_system_checks_and_reduces_to_the_right_branch() {
        let k = base_env();
        // A closed system needs `i` to be a real bound interval variable: build it
        // inside a `PLam` so `Var(0) : I` is in scope, then specialize by `instantiate`.
        let i = Term::Var(0);
        let sys_body = Term::sys(vec![(Cof::eq0(i.clone()), cn("a").lift(1, 0)), (Cof::eq1(i), cn("b").lift(1, 0))]);
        let ty_body = Term::partial(Cof::or(Cof::eq0(Term::Var(0)), Cof::eq1(Term::Var(0))), cn("A").lift(1, 0));
        // Check the whole path abstraction `Ôƒ¿iÔƒ® sys_body : Ôƒ¿iÔƒ® ty_body`... simpler:
        // check directly under a manually extended context.
        let mut ctx = crate::check::LocalCtx::new();
        ctx.push(Term::I);
        k.checker().check(&mut ctx, &sys_body, &ty_body).unwrap();

        // Specializing at i0/i1 and reducing must pick the matching branch.
        let at_i0 = sys_body.instantiate(&Term::IZero);
        let at_i1 = sys_body.instantiate(&Term::IOne);
        let reducer = crate::reduce::Reducer::new(k.env());
        assert!(reducer.is_def_eq(&at_i0, &cn("a")));
        assert!(reducer.is_def_eq(&at_i1, &cn("b")));

        // Differentially: NbE agrees.
        let nbe = crate::nbe::Nbe::new(k.env());
        assert!(nbe.conv(&at_i0, &cn("a")));
        assert!(nbe.conv(&at_i1, &cn("b")));
    }

    /// **Adversarial**: an incompatible system ÔÇö two branches disagreeing on a
    /// *satisfiable* overlap ÔÇö is rejected by the compatibility condition.
    #[test]
    fn incompatible_system_is_rejected() {
        let k = base_env();
        // Both branches guarded by `Ôèñ`, so their overlap is `Ôèñ` (satisfiable) ÔÇö but
        // they disagree (`a` vs `b`, distinct axioms). Must be rejected.
        let ty = Term::partial(Cof::top(), cn("A"));
        let sys = Term::sys(vec![(Cof::top(), cn("a")), (Cof::top(), cn("b"))]);
        let err = k.check(&sys, &ty).unwrap_err();
        assert!(err.contains("incompatible"), "got: {err}");
    }

    /// A system that doesn't cover its expected guard is rejected (coverage
    /// obligation `¤ê Ôèó ¤å_1 Ôê¿ ÔÇª Ôê¿ ¤å_n`).
    #[test]
    fn non_covering_system_is_rejected() {
        let k = base_env();
        let ty = Term::partial(Cof::top(), cn("A")); // needs to be defined *everywhere*
        let sys = Term::sys(vec![(Cof::eq0(Term::IZero), cn("a"))]); // only covers Ôèñ trivially? eq0(IZero) simplifies to Top actually
        // Use a genuinely partial guard instead: an axiom-free open variable is not
        // available at top level, so instead under-cover with `ÔèÑ`, which never
        // covers `Ôèñ`.
        let sys2 = Term::sys(vec![(Cof::bot(), cn("a"))]);
        let _ = sys; // (eq0(IZero) is actually Top and *would* cover ÔÇö avoid asserting on it)
        let err = k.check(&sys2, &ty).unwrap_err();
        assert!(err.contains("cover"), "got: {err}");
    }

    /// **Adversarial**: an incompatible system cannot be used to prove `False`
    /// (equate two distinct closed values) via `Empty`'s eliminator or otherwise ÔÇö
    /// concretely, the checker rejects it outright before any such derivation could
    /// even be attempted (see `incompatible_system_is_rejected`); here we further
    /// confirm that even a *compatible* system between two propositionally-typed
    /// terms cannot be abused to fabricate a term of an unrelated (empty) axiom type,
    /// since `Sys` only ever emits one of the branches you already had to
    /// type-check at `A` ÔÇö nothing manufactures a value of an uninhabited type `E`.
    #[test]
    fn compatible_system_cannot_conjure_an_inhabitant_of_an_unrelated_axiom() {
        let mut k = base_env();
        k.add_axiom("E", 0, Term::typ(0)).unwrap(); // an axiom type with *no* introduced terms
        let ty = Term::partial(Cof::top(), cn("E"));
        // No term of type `E` exists to put in a branch, so the only way to attempt
        // this is to reuse `a : A` at the wrong type ÔÇö which `check_sys`'s per-branch
        // `self.check(ctx, t, a)` (against `E`, not `A`) correctly rejects.
        let sys = Term::sys(vec![(Cof::top(), cn("a"))]);
        assert!(k.check(&sys, &ty).is_err());
    }

    /// **Adversarial**: `Sys`/`Partial` still can't equate two distinct closed
    /// values ÔÇö a stuck system (no branch decided) is not definitionally equal to
    /// an arbitrary term merely because it's "some system or other".
    #[test]
    fn stuck_system_is_not_equated_with_an_unrelated_value() {
        let k = base_env();
        // Build a system whose guard mentions a genuinely free interval variable
        // (never resolved to i0/i1), so no branch fires: it stays stuck.
        let mut ctx = crate::check::LocalCtx::new();
        ctx.push(Term::I);
        let sys = Term::sys(vec![(Cof::eq0(Term::Var(0)), cn("a").lift(1, 0))]);
        assert!(!k.checker().is_def_eq(&mut ctx, &sys, &cn("b").lift(1, 0)));
    }

    /// **Adversarial**: `I`/cofibration machinery still can't flow into a fibrant
    /// `Type` position ÔÇö a `╬á` domain built directly from `I` is rejected exactly as
    /// in Phase 1 (this doesn't change with `Partial`/`Sys` added: `Partial ¤å A`'s
    /// own domain-of-quantification is still ordinary `A`, and nothing here lets a
    /// bare `Cof`/interval term stand in for a `Sort`).
    #[test]
    fn interval_still_cannot_be_a_pi_domain_with_partial_in_scope() {
        let mut k = Kernel::new();
        let err = k.add_axiom("bad", 0, Term::pi(Term::I, Term::typ(0))).unwrap_err();
        assert!(err.contains('I'), "got: {err}");
    }

    /// Empty system `[]` is only valid against a provably-`ÔèÑ` guard.
    #[test]
    fn empty_system_requires_false_guard() {
        let k = base_env();
        let ty_ok = Term::partial(Cof::bot(), cn("A"));
        k.check(&Term::sys(vec![]), &ty_ok).unwrap();
        let ty_bad = Term::partial(Cof::top(), cn("A"));
        assert!(k.check(&Term::sys(vec![]), &ty_bad).is_err());
    }

    /// `Sys` has no type of its own to *infer* ÔÇö it's check-only.
    #[test]
    fn sys_cannot_be_inferred() {
        let k = base_env();
        let sys = Term::sys(vec![(Cof::top(), cn("a"))]);
        assert!(k.infer(&sys).is_err());
    }
}
